   2025},
Organization = {National Security Agency},
Abstract = {Cybersecurity dominates global concerns as the need for better tools, a
   better-equipped workforce, and better solutions that outpace the
   sophistication and amplitude of yearly cyberattacks continues. To
   address these needs, research in cyber operations, defenses, and digital
   forensics must remain at the forefront of private and public sector
   focus. As new research in applied machine learning and artificial
   intelligence (AI) advances our field of knowledge, new tools with
   state-of-the-art techniques can begin to make their way into the hands
   of our cyber defenders. This mini-track covers the broad spectrum of
   these areas and provides new contributions in the areas of operational
   technology (OT) security (A Zero Trust Architecture for Critical
   Operational Technology Systems), forgery detection (Image Domain
   Distinct Native Attribute Fingerprinting for Image Forgery
   Classification), and threat detection (sysBERT: Improved Behavioral
   Malware Detection using BERT Trained on sys2vec Embeddings and
   Development of a Neuromorphic-Friendly Spiking Neural Network for RF
   Event-based Classification). Collectively the track provides new
   directions for cyber operations, defense, and forensics research.},
