   Networks},
Year = {2024},
Pages = {1453-1459},
Note = {16th International Conference on Computational Intelligence and
   Communication Networks, Indore, INDIA, DEC 22-23, 2024},
Organization = {Oriental University Indore; Institute of Electrical and Electronics
   Engineers Inc},
Abstract = {Insecurity is a growing concern in Latin America and some parts of the
   world, and the city of Lima is no exception. Crimes such as assaults,
   robberies and other crimes are on the rise, generating great concern
   among the population. In this context, it is important to interact with
   the population by geo-referencing danger zones with crime maps. This
   paper aims to develop a real-time application that allows the tracking
   and monitoring of danger zones, using machine learning techniques and
   visualization of critical zones. The methodology uses a dataset of crime
   reports provided by the Peruvian Police from 2018 to 2023, using tools
   such as Power BI and libraries such as Pandas, Plotly, and Mapbox from
   Python to extract latitude and longitude.The process includes data
   analysis and prediction, application development, interactive map
   creation, data visualization, and application testing. The study
   concludes that crime mapping is a valuable tool for combating
   insecurity. Integrating crime data with georeferencing technologies
   allows detailed visualization of crime patterns, enabling better
   resource planning, prioritization, and data-driven decision-making to
   address criminal activity effectively.},
